Note:
Runa Lexer: Comprehensive Test Suite

This module tests the new world-class lexer architecture with encapsulated state,
robust longest-match logic, and AI-first case-insensitive design.

Key Test Areas:
- Basic tokenization functionality
- Case-insensitive variable handling
- Multi-word operator recognition
- Error handling and recovery
- Natural language syntax support
:End Note

Note: Import the new lexer modules
Import "src/runa/compiler/lexer/lexer.runa"
Import "src/runa/compiler/lexer/token.runa"
Import "src/runa/compiler/lexer/diagnostics.runa"

Note: Test Suite Runner
Process called "run_lexer_test_suite" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Run all lexer tests and return results
    Let results be dictionary containing
    Let total_tests be 0
    Let passed_tests be 0
    Let failed_tests be 0
    
    Note: Run basic tokenization tests
    Let basic_results be run_basic_tokenization_tests
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus basic_results.total_tests
    Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus basic_results.passed_tests
    Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus basic_results.failed_tests
    
    Note: Run case-insensitive tests
    Let case_results be run_case_insensitive_tests
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus case_results.total_tests
    Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus case_results.passed_tests
    Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus case_results.failed_tests
    
    Note: Run multi-word operator tests
    Let operator_results be run_multi_word_operator_tests
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus operator_results.total_tests
    Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus operator_results.passed_tests
    Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus operator_results.failed_tests
    
    Note: Run error handling tests
    Let error_results be run_error_handling_tests
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus error_results.total_tests
    Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus error_results.passed_tests
    Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus error_results.failed_tests
    
    Note: Run natural language tests
    Let natural_results be run_natural_language_tests
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus natural_results.total_tests
    Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus natural_results.passed_tests
    Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus natural_results.failed_tests
    
    Set results.total_tests to total_tests
    Set results.passed_tests to passed_tests
    Set results.failed_tests to failed_tests
    Set results.success_rate to ((passed_tests multiplied by 100) divided by total_tests)
    
    Return results

Note: Basic Tokenization Tests
Process called "run_basic_tokenization_tests" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test basic tokenization functionality
    Let total_tests be 0
    Let passed_tests be 0
    Let failed_tests be 0
    
    Note: Test simple variable declaration
    Let test1_result be test_simple_variable_declaration
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test1_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Note: Test number literals
    Let test2_result be test_number_literals
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test2_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Note: Test string literals
    Let test3_result be test_string_literals
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test3_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Note: Test indentation
    Let test4_result be test_indentation
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test4_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Return dictionary containing:
        "total_tests" as total_tests
        "passed_tests" as passed_tests
        "failed_tests" as failed_tests

Process called "test_simple_variable_declaration" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test simple variable declaration tokenization
    Let source be "Let x be 42"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    If length of tokens is not equal to 4:
        Return false
    
    Let token1 be tokens at index 0
    Let token2 be tokens at index 1
    Let token3 be tokens at index 2
    Let token4 be tokens at index 3
    
    Return token1.type is equal to LET_KEYWORD and
           token1.value is equal to "Let" and
           token2.type is equal to IDENTIFIER and
           token2.value is equal to "x" and
           token3.type is equal to BE_KEYWORD and
           token3.value is equal to "be" and
           token4.type is equal to INTEGER_LITERAL and
           token4.value is equal to "42"

Process called "test_number_literals" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test number literal tokenization
    Let source be "Let pi be 3.14 and count be 42"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let float_token be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as FLOAT_LITERAL
    Let int_token be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as INTEGER_LITERAL
    
    Return length of float_token is equal to 1 and
           (float_token at index 0).value is equal to "3.14" and
           length of int_token is equal to 1 and
           (int_token at index 0).value is equal to "42"

Process called "test_string_literals" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test string literal tokenization
    Let source be "Let message be \"Hello, World!\""
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let string_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as STRING_LITERAL
    
    Return length of string_tokens is equal to 1 and
           (string_tokens at index 0).value is equal to "\"Hello, World!\""

Process called "test_indentation" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test indentation tokenization
    Let source be "If x is greater than 0:\n    Display x\n    Set x to x minus 1"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let indent_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as INDENT
    Let dedent_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as DEDENT
    
    Return length of indent_tokens is greater than 0 and
           length of dedent_tokens is greater than 0

Note: Case-Insensitive Tests
Process called "run_case_insensitive_tests" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test case-insensitive variable and keyword handling
    Let total_tests be 0
    Let passed_tests be 0
    Let failed_tests be 0
    
    Note: Test case-insensitive keywords
    Let test1_result be test_case_insensitive_keywords
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test1_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Note: Test case-insensitive variables
    Let test2_result be test_case_insensitive_variables
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test2_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Note: Test multi-word variable normalization
    Let test3_result be test_multi_word_variable_normalization
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test3_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Return dictionary containing:
        "total_tests" as total_tests
        "passed_tests" as passed_tests
        "failed_tests" as failed_tests

Process called "test_case_insensitive_keywords" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test that keywords are case-insensitive
    Let source1 be "Let x be 42"
    Let source2 be "let x be 42"
    Let source3 be "LET x BE 42"
    
    Let tokens1 be tokenize with source_code as source1 and file_path as "test1.runa"
    Let tokens2 be tokenize with source_code as source2 and file_path as "test2.runa"
    Let tokens3 be tokenize with source_code as source3 and file_path as "test3.runa"
    
    Let let_token1 be tokens1 at index 0
    Let let_token2 be tokens2 at index 0
    Let let_token3 be tokens3 at index 0
    
    Return let_token1.type is equal to LET_KEYWORD and
           let_token2.type is equal to LET_KEYWORD and
           let_token3.type is equal to LET_KEYWORD and
           tokens_equal with token1 as let_token1 and token2 as let_token2 and
           tokens_equal with token1 as let_token2 and token2 as let_token3

Process called "test_case_insensitive_variables" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test that variables are case-insensitive
    Let source be "Let MyVariable be 42\nLet myvariable be 24"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let identifier_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as IDENTIFIER
    
    If length of identifier_tokens is less than 2:
        Return false
    
    Let var1 be identifier_tokens at index 0
    Let var2 be identifier_tokens at index 1
    
    Return tokens_equal with token1 as var1 and token2 as var2

Process called "test_multi_word_variable_normalization" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test multi-word variable normalization
    Let source be "Let My Variable be 42\nLet my variable be 24"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let qualified_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as QUALIFIED_IDENTIFIER
    
    If length of qualified_tokens is less than 2:
        Return false
    
    Let var1 be qualified_tokens at index 0
    Let var2 be qualified_tokens at index 1
    
    Return tokens_equal with token1 as var1 and token2 as var2

Note: Multi-Word Operator Tests
Process called "run_multi_word_operator_tests" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test multi-word operator recognition
    Let total_tests be 0
    Let passed_tests be 0
    Let failed_tests be 0
    
    Note: Test comparison operators
    Let test1_result be test_comparison_operators
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test1_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Note: Test arithmetic operators
    Let test2_result be test_arithmetic_operators
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test2_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Note: Test longest match logic
    Let test3_result be test_longest_match_logic
    Set total_tests to total_tests plus 1
    If test3_result:
        Set passed_tests to passed_tests plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_tests to failed_tests plus 1
    
    Return dictionary containing:
        "total_tests" as total_tests
        "passed_tests" as passed_tests
        "failed_tests" as failed_tests

Process called "test_comparison_operators" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test comparison operator recognition
    Let source be "If x is greater than 0 and y is less than 10"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let operator_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as OPERATOR
    
    Let has_greater_than be false
    Let has_less_than be false
    
    For each token in operator_tokens:
        If token.normalized_value is equal to "is greater than":
            Set has_greater_than to true
        Otherwise if token.normalized_value is equal to "is less than":
            Set has_less_than to true
    
    Return has_greater_than and has_less_than

Process called "test_arithmetic_operators" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test arithmetic operator recognition
    Let source be "Let result be a plus b multiplied by c"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let operator_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as OPERATOR
    
    Let has_plus be false
    Let has_multiplied_by be false
    
    For each token in operator_tokens:
        If token.normalized_value is equal to "plus":
            Set has_plus to true
        Otherwise if token.normalized_value is equal to "multiplied by":
            Set has_multiplied_by to true
    
    Return has_plus and has_multiplied_by

Process called "test_longest_match_logic" returns Boolean:
    Note: Test that longest match logic works correctly
    Let source be "If x is greater than or equal to 0"
    Let tokens be tokenize with source_code as source and file_path as "test.runa"
    
    Let operator_tokens be find_tokens_by_type with tokens as tokens and token_type as OPERATOR
    
    For each token in operator_tokens:
        If token.normalized_value is equal to "is greater than or equal to":
            Return true
    
    Return false

Note: Error Handling Tests
